<div class="content">
  <h1 class="title">Frequently asked questions</h1>
  <div class="faq_block">
    <b>What is a passmoji?</b>
    <br />
    <i>A passmoji is a password that uses emojis instead of regular characters.</i>
  </div>

  <div class="faq_block">
    <b>Are you serious?</b>
    <br />
    <i>No!</i>
  </div>

  <div class="faq_block">
    <b>Why should I use a passmoji instead as a password?</b>
    <br />
    <i>Because emojis are cuter than letters and numbers.</i>
  </div>

  <div class="faq_block">
    <b>Is my passmoji safer than regular (typeable) passwords made from letters, numbers and special characters?</b>
    <br />
    <i>Nope, not really ... and it also brings new challenges.</i>
  </div>

  <div class="faq_block">
    <b>Can I use my passmoji everywhere?</b>
    <br />
    <i>Yes, as long as you can type (or copy/paste) it and the service supports unicode characters in the password.
    Please make sure the service really supports emojis in passwords or you might not be able to log in again.</i>
    <br />
    See <a href="https://thenextweb.com/apple/2015/12/16/dont-make-the-same-mistake-as-this-guy-and-set-your-password-as-an-emoji" target="_blank">here</a> for an example of what can happen if emojis are used in the wrong place.
  </div>

  <div class="faq_block">
    <b>What is a good (and safe) password?</b>
    <br />
    <i>Have a look <a href="/password">here</a> for more information about good passwords.</i>
  </div>
</div>
